										<content:encoded><![CDATA[
<p class="has-text-align-center" style="font-size:20px;max-width:600px"> <strong>1.Apps having trouble showing notifications</strong></p>



<p style="max-width:600px">Go to settings search for Gmail app and stop battery optimizing </p>



<ul style="font-size:17px"><li>Go to setting then search for optimise battery usage </li><li>Then Tap on Apps not optimised (a drop down menu will drop) select All</li><li>Now search for <strong>Gmail</strong></li><li>Tap on it (This might not fix the issue on your devices so keep sync on from your notification center)</li></ul>



<figure class="wp-block-image size-large is-resized"><img src="https://i0.wp.com/thetechjournalist.site/wp-content/uploads/2022/04/Screenshot_20220428-235008_Settings-1.jpg?resize=237%2C516&#038;ssl=1" alt="App Settings on Samsung A32 4g " class="wp-image-1768" width="237" height="516" data-recalc-dims="1" /><figcaption>App Settings on Samsung A32 4g </figcaption></figure>



<h5 class="has-text-align-center" id="h-2-make-your-android-little-faster" style="font-size:25px"><strong>2. Make your android little faster </strong></h5>



<p style="font-size:17px;max-width:600px">Check for running background apps from <strong>Developer</strong> options </p>



<p class="has-small-font-size"><strong>*i.e this was tested on Android 11 device. we are not/will not take any responsible/ity if your device takes any damage* </strong></p>



<ul class="has-regular-font-size"><li>Go to settings scroll down for developer option</li><li>If you don&#8217;t see it anywhere near <strong>About phone</strong> </li><li>Now enter Developer option scroll down all the way to <strong>Background Check</strong> or search it</li><li>Press on the option and deselect every app or package that is turned on  </li></ul>



<figure class="wp-block-image size-large is-resized"><img loading="lazy" src="https://i0.wp.com/thetechjournalist.site/wp-content/uploads/2022/04/Screenshot_20220429-001521_Settings.jpg?resize=244%2C536&#038;ssl=1" alt="Developer Settings on Samsung A32 4g " class="wp-image-1769" width="244" height="536" data-recalc-dims="1" /><figcaption>Developer Settings on Samsung A32 4g </figcaption></figure>



<p style="font-size:25px;max-width:600px"><strong>3.Turn of Nearby Device Scanning</strong></p>



<ul><li>Go to settings select <strong>Connections </strong></li><li>Select <strong>More connection settings</strong></li><li>Turn off <strong>Nearby device scanning </strong></li></ul>



<figure class="wp-block-image size-large is-resized"><img loading="lazy" src="https://i0.wp.com/thetechjournalist.site/wp-content/uploads/2022/04/Screenshot_20220429-002629_Settings.jpg?resize=260%2C568&#038;ssl=1" alt="Connection Settings on Samsung A32 4g " class="wp-image-1770" width="260" height="568" data-recalc-dims="1" /><figcaption>Connection Settings on Samsung A32 4g </figcaption></figure>



